[Crying Continues]

236
00:20:48,100 --> 00:20:50,900
Oh, my God.

237
00:20:56,700 --> 00:20:59,100
It could not be better.

238
00:20:59,200 --> 00:21:02,900
It could be worse.
How? Tell me.

239
00:21:03,000 --> 00:21:05,900
[Shouting]
How on earth could it
possibly be worse?

240
00:21:06,000 --> 00:21:08,000
[Slams Down Suitcase]

241
00:21:08,000 --> 00:21:10,700
[Man]
Dzien dobry.

242
00:21:10,700 --> 00:21:13,100
Dzien dobry.
Dzien dobry.

243
00:21:13,200 --> 00:21:15,000
Dzien dobry.

244
00:21:15,000 --> 00:21:17,500
Dzien dobry.
Dzien dobry.

245
00:21:17,500 --> 00:21:20,400
[Indistinct German]

246
00:21:20,500 --> 00:21:22,900
Hey, Goldberg.
Poldek.

247
00:21:23,000 --> 00:21:27,300
What's this?
Uh, the Judenrat has
its own police now.

248
00:21:27,400 --> 00:21:30,200
You don't say.
Ordnungsdienst.

249
00:21:30,300 --> 00:21:32,800
I'm a policeman now,
could you believe it?
It's hard to believe.

250
00:21:32,900 --> 00:21:34,900
Oh, no,
it's not hard
to believe.

251
00:21:34,900 --> 00:21:37,400
It's a good racket, Poldek.
The only racket here.

252
00:21:37,400 --> 00:21:40,900
Look, maybe I could
put in a good word for you
with my superiors.

253
00:21:40,900 --> 00:21:45,200
Your superiors?
Come on, they are not
as bad as everyone says.

254
00:21:45,300 --> 00:21:48,500
Well, they're worse
than everyone says,
but it's a lot of money.

255
00:21:48,600 --> 00:21:51,200
A lot of money.

256
00:21:51,300 --> 00:21:54,000
Give me my
housing assignment.

257
00:21:54,100 --> 00:21:58,500
Come on.
You look funny
in that hat, Goldberg.

258
00:21:58,600 --> 00:22:02,000
[Laughs]
You look like a clown,
you know?

259
00:22:07,000 --> 00:22:09,400
[Stern]
He's a very important man.

260
00:22:09,400 --> 00:22:11,200
Just give him
two minutes of your time.

261
00:22:11,300 --> 00:22:14,700
Since when did time cost money?
Just sit down and listen.

262
00:22:14,800 --> 00:22:17,000
Please.
Sir?

263
00:22:20,700 --> 00:22:22,800
[Schindler]
For each thousand you invest,
I will repay you with...

264
00:22:22,800 --> 00:22:25,000
Two hundred.
200 kilos
of enamelware a month,

265
00:22:25,100 --> 00:22:27,000
to begin in July
and to continue
for one year.

266
00:22:27,100 --> 00:22:30,900
After which time, we're even.
That's it. It's very simple.

267
00:22:30,900 --> 00:22:33,900
Not good enough.
It's not
good enough.

268
00:22:33,900 --> 00:22:36,200
Not good enough?

269
00:22:36,300 --> 00:22:40,400
Look where you're living.
Look where you've been put.
''Not good enough.''

270
00:22:40,500 --> 00:22:43,000
A couple of months ago you'd
be right, not anymore.

271
00:22:43,100 --> 00:22:46,200
Money's still money.

272
00:22:47,800 --> 00:22:50,100
No, it is not.

273
00:22:50,100 --> 00:22:52,200
That's why we're here.

274
00:22:52,300 --> 00:22:54,300
Trade goods--
that's the only currency...

275
00:22:54,300 --> 00:22:56,300
that'll be worth
anything in the ghetto.

276
00:22:56,300 --> 00:22:59,700
Things have changed,
my friend.

277
00:23:00,500 --> 00:23:02,900
Did I call
this meeting?

278
00:23:03,000 --> 00:23:05,400
You told Mr. Stern
you wanted to speak to me.

279
00:23:05,500 --> 00:23:08,100
I'm here.
I've made you a fair offer.

280
00:23:08,100 --> 00:23:12,100
Fair would be
a percentage in the company.

281
00:23:12,200 --> 00:23:15,400
[Laughing]
Forget the whole thing.

282
00:23:15,500 --> 00:23:17,800
Get out.

283
00:23:22,000 --> 00:23:25,100
How do we know that you
will do what you say?

284
00:23:25,100 --> 00:23:27,100
Because I said I would.

285
00:23:27,100 --> 00:23:29,400
You want a contract?
To be upheld by what court?

286
00:23:29,400 --> 00:23:32,400
I said what I'll do.
That's our contract.

287
00:23:32,400 --> 00:23:35,800
[Indistinct Polish]

288
00:23:35,800 --> 00:23:38,000
...mielismy racje.

289
00:23:49,700 --> 00:23:55,100
[Man]
Piec, szesc, siedem...

290
00:23:55,200 --> 00:23:58,800
osiem, dziewiec.

291
00:24:01,500 --> 00:24:05,400
[Machinery Buzzes]

292
00:24:07,000 --> 00:24:09,900
[Schindler Clapping]

293
00:24:10,300 --> 00:24:14,600
The standard SS rate for
Jewish skilled labor
is seven marks a day,

294
00:24:14,600 --> 00:24:17,600
five for unskilled
and women.

295
00:24:17,700 --> 00:24:20,700
This is what you pay
the Reich Economic Office.

296
00:24:20,800 --> 00:24:23,300
TheJews themselves
receive nothing.

297
00:24:23,400 --> 00:24:27,800
Poles you pay wages.
Generally, they get
a little more.

298
00:24:27,900 --> 00:24:30,500
Are you
listening?
What was that about the SS?

299
00:24:30,600 --> 00:24:32,800
The rate? The what?

300
00:24:32,900 --> 00:24:36,500
TheJewish worker's salary--
you pay it directly to
the SS, not to the worker.

301
00:24:36,600 --> 00:24:38,700
He gets nothing.
But it's less.

302
00:24:38,700 --> 00:24:40,800
It's less than what
I would pay a Pole.
It's less.

303
00:24:40,900 --> 00:24:43,800
That's the point
I'm trying to make.

304
00:24:43,900 --> 00:24:46,500
Poles cost more.

305
00:24:46,600 --> 00:24:51,200
[Sniffs]
Why should I hire Poles?

306
00:24:51,300 --> 00:24:55,200
An enamelware factory
over at, uh, Lipowa Street.

307
00:24:55,300 --> 00:24:58,200
It, uh, it, um--
It's owned by a German.

308
00:24:58,300 --> 00:25:01,400
But it's outside
the ghetto, so you can
barter for extra goods--

309
00:25:01,400 --> 00:25:03,700
for eggs, I don't know
what you need--

310
00:25:03,800 --> 00:25:05,900
with the Polish workers.
You can't get it here.

311
00:25:05,900 --> 00:25:10,200
Also, he's asking for ten
healthy women for the--
I am healthy.

312
00:25:10,300 --> 00:25:13,300
[Crowd Laughing]
Bring your sister, okay?

313
00:25:13,400 --> 00:25:17,500
[Shouting Orders
In German And Polish]

314
00:25:17,600 --> 00:25:20,000
Chodz.

315
00:25:20,100 --> 00:25:23,500
You need to convince them
you have a trade, something
valuable to the war effort.

316
00:25:23,600 --> 00:25:25,800
Like what?
What if you don't?
I'm a musician.

317
00:25:25,900 --> 00:25:29,500
Your name goes on a list.
And they put you on trucks--

318
00:25:29,600 --> 00:25:31,700
No, no, no, 
that's not true.
You're a musician?

319
00:25:31,800 --> 00:25:34,300
Yeah.
I'd find a good
hiding place if I were you.

320
00:25:34,400 --> 00:25:38,900
I'm not going to hide
like some animal.
There are places to hide.

321
00:25:38,900 --> 00:25:43,400
[Whistle Blowing]

322
00:25:43,500 --> 00:25:45,400
Der Naechste!

323
00:25:45,500 --> 00:25:48,900
I'm a graduate
of the University of Lwow.

324
00:25:48,900 --> 00:25:52,200
I used to work at the
hydroelectric station
in Roznow--

325
00:25:52,300 --> 00:25:54,200
Blauschein.

326
00:25:57,500 --> 00:26:01,400
I'm gonna get the necessary
papers because this card
is no good anymore.

327
00:26:01,500 --> 00:26:03,900
You can stay in this line
all day, you'll still get
one of these.

328
00:26:04,000 --> 00:26:07,700
They are no good.
You'll have to leave
the line now,

329
00:26:07,800 --> 00:26:12,400
then you'll get a blue card,
a Blauschein, to say that
you are an essential worker.

330
00:26:12,500 --> 00:26:15,600
I'll get these papers
for you at Pankiewicz.

331
00:26:15,600 --> 00:26:17,600
Pharmacist.
Just there, look.

332
00:26:17,700 --> 00:26:19,600
Guess who is here?

333
00:26:19,700 --> 00:26:22,400
[Goldberg]
Poldek! Enjoying
the weather, Poldek?

334
00:26:22,500 --> 00:26:25,500
Enjoying the lines?
Need some shoe polish?

335
00:26:25,500 --> 00:26:28,100
In a metal container
maybe?
[Goldberg Laughs]

336
00:26:28,100 --> 00:26:32,600
Not essential?
I think you misunderstand
the meaning of the word.

337
00:26:32,700 --> 00:26:35,600
No Blauschein, sir.
Stand over there.

338
00:26:35,700 --> 00:26:38,500
Move. Next!

339
00:26:38,600 --> 00:26:40,800
What do you mean,
''Not essential''?

340
00:26:40,900 --> 00:26:46,600
I teach history and literature.
Since when is not essential?

341
00:26:51,900 --> 00:26:54,300
He's a metal polisher.

342
00:27:01,200 --> 00:27:04,000
It was not right?
It's very good.
He's 53 years old.

343
00:27:04,100 --> 00:27:07,200
It's too new.
Mmm.
Thank you.

344
00:27:15,400 --> 00:27:17,900
You're crazy.
You left it
in your drawer.

345
00:27:17,900 --> 00:27:20,200
How many times
have I told you?

346
00:27:20,300 --> 00:27:23,000
Your work certificate
you keep in your pocket
at all times.

347
00:27:23,100 --> 00:27:25,000
And you leave everything
in your drawer.

348
00:27:25,100 --> 00:27:27,500
[Stern]
How many times I've told you?

349
00:27:27,600 --> 00:27:30,800
I'm a metal polisher.

350
00:27:39,600 --> 00:27:42,200
[Man]
Take the round sheet of tin,

351
00:27:42,300 --> 00:27:46,200
dip it in soap emulsion.

352
00:27:46,300 --> 00:27:51,400
[Liquid Splashing]
Then place it centrally
in the press.

353
00:28:06,600 --> 00:28:10,000
We obtain the soup pot.
The soup pot.

354
00:28:10,100 --> 00:28:13,500
Soup pot.

355
00:28:13,600 --> 00:28:16,700
Grosz, Mrs. Grosz,
stay together.

356
00:28:21,000 --> 00:28:26,200
Sir, I have ten work permits
here for the Deutsche
Emailwarenfabrik,

357
00:28:26,200 --> 00:28:29,100
cosigned by Mr. Bankier
and myself.

358
00:28:29,100 --> 00:28:33,800
[Foreman]
If it's carbonized,
clean it with a file.

359
00:28:33,900 --> 00:28:38,700
But don't touch
both the electrodes
at the same time.

360
00:28:38,700 --> 00:28:41,900
You'll get electrocuted.
Here, have a try.

361
00:28:46,300 --> 00:28:48,700
[Foreman]
Roll the metal
under the press,

362
00:28:48,800 --> 00:28:51,200
but be very careful
unless you want your fingers...

363
00:28:51,300 --> 00:28:54,100
to become part
of the teapot.

364
00:28:55,700 --> 00:28:59,400
Occupation?
I'm a writer.
I play the flute.

365
00:28:59,400 --> 00:29:02,900
But Moses is
a skilled metalworker.

366
00:29:02,900 --> 00:29:05,200
He can make tin pots.
He can make tanks.

367
00:29:05,300 --> 00:29:07,200
He can make whatever
Mr. Schindler asks.

368
00:29:07,300 --> 00:29:09,900
He's highly skilled.
Give him your card.

369
00:29:09,900 --> 00:29:12,300
Moses, give him your card.

370
00:29:14,400 --> 00:29:16,700
[Foreman]
Now, dip the basin
with the tongs...

371
00:29:16,800 --> 00:29:19,300
into the enamel solution.

372
00:29:21,400 --> 00:29:25,800
And after swiveling it around,
carefully place it aside
to drip dry.

373
00:29:28,800 --> 00:29:32,300
And whatever he asks you,
allow me just to represent
you and speak for you.

374
00:29:32,400 --> 00:29:34,400
Don't say a word.

375
00:29:34,500 --> 00:29:38,000
[Schindler]
Filing, billing, keeping track
of my appointments, shorthand.

376
00:29:38,000 --> 00:29:42,300
Typing, obviously.
How is your typing?
Uh, all right.

377
00:29:42,400 --> 00:29:44,300
Please.

378
00:29:52,200 --> 00:29:57,100
[Typing Slowly]

379
00:29:57,200 --> 00:30:00,400
[Typing Slowly]

380
00:30:00,500 --> 00:30:04,000
[Typing Slowly,
Bell Rings]

381
00:30:09,600 --> 00:30:13,100
[Typing
Extremely Slow]

382
00:30:18,700 --> 00:30:21,500
[Barely Typing]

383
00:30:26,000 --> 00:30:28,900
[Typing Quickly]

384
00:30:37,200 --> 00:30:40,900
You need a secretary.
Pick one.

385
00:30:40,900 --> 00:30:45,900
I don't know how.
They're all so...
qualified.

386
00:30:45,900 --> 00:30:48,900
You have to choose.

387
00:30:48,900 --> 00:30:51,100
[Sighs]

388
00:30:51,200 --> 00:30:54,000
Prosze sie ladnie usmiechac.
Big smile.
Big smile.

389
00:30:54,000 --> 00:30:55,500
Uwaga.

390
00:30:55,500 --> 00:30:58,000
[Camera Shutter Clicks]

391
00:30:59,700 --> 00:31:01,900
####[Piano]

392
00:31:15,000 --> 00:31:17,900
If you would,
look after my guest.

393
00:31:18,000 --> 00:31:23,300
[Schindler]
Um, boxed teas are good.
Coffiee, pate, um...

394
00:31:23,300 --> 00:31:27,500
kielbasa sausage,
cheeses, Beluga caviar.
Yes.

395
00:31:27,600 --> 00:31:29,400
And, of course, who could live
without German cigarettes?

396
00:31:29,500 --> 00:31:31,700
Get me as many
as you can fid.

397
00:31:31,800 --> 00:31:33,900
And some more fresh fruit.

398
00:31:34,000 --> 00:31:36,800
The real rarities--
oranges, lemons, pineapples.

399
00:31:36,800 --> 00:31:39,600
I need several boxes
of Cuban cigars. The best.
Yes.

400
00:31:39,600 --> 00:31:43,400
And dark, unsweetened chocolate.
Not in the shape ofladyfigers,
the chunk chocolate.

401
00:31:43,500 --> 00:31:46,600
Yes.
Big as my hand,
you sample at wine tastings.

402
00:31:46,700 --> 00:31:49,900
We're going to need lots
of cognac. The best, Hennessy.

403
00:31:50,000 --> 00:31:55,400
Dom Perignon champagne.
Um, get L 'espadon sardines...

404
00:31:55,500 --> 00:31:58,500
and, oh,
try to fid nylon stockings.

405
00:32:01,000 --> 00:32:04,200
[Schindler]
It is my distinct pleasure
to announce...

406
00:32:04,300 --> 00:32:09,900
the fully operational status
of Deutsche Email Fabrik...

407
00:32:10,000 --> 00:32:11,300
[Foreman]
Patrzjakies szmaty!

408
00:32:11,300 --> 00:32:14,800
manufacturers of superior
enamelware crockery...

409
00:32:14,800 --> 00:32:20,300
expressly designed
and crafted for military use.

410
00:32:20,300 --> 00:32:23,000
Utilizing only
the most modern equipment,

411
00:32:23,100 --> 00:32:28,200
D.E.F. 's staffi of
highly-skilled and experienced
artisans andjourneymen...

412
00:32:28,200 --> 00:32:31,800
deliver a product
of unparalleled quality,

413
00:32:31,900 --> 00:32:35,800
enabling me to proffier,
with absolute confidence
and pride,

414
00:32:35,900 --> 00:32:38,500
a full line
of field and kitchenware...

415
00:32:38,600 --> 00:32:42,700
unsurpassable in all respects
by my competitors.

416
00:32:42,800 --> 00:32:45,400
See attached list
and available colors.

417
00:32:45,500 --> 00:32:50,300
Anticipating the enclosed bids
will meet with your approval.

418
00:32:50,400 --> 00:32:54,200
Made in Havana, Cuba.
Looking forward to a long and
mutually prosperous association.

419
00:32:54,300 --> 00:32:57,500
Look at this.
I extend to you in advance
my sincerest gratitude...

420
00:32:57,600 --> 00:33:00,500
and very best regards.
Oskar Schindler.

421
00:33:00,600 --> 00:33:04,000
Yeah, I need 700 gross
from here for next Thursday.

422
00:33:04,100 --> 00:33:06,900
Nine hundred--
No, make it ten
for Wednesday.

423
00:33:06,900 --> 00:33:10,800
All this stuff here goes
to Madritsch's factory
on Tuesday of next week.

424
00:33:18,700 --> 00:33:22,400
[Horn Honking]

425
00:33:26,600 --> 00:33:30,000
[Schindler]
My father was fond of saying,
''You need three things in life

426
00:33:30,100 --> 00:33:34,200
''a good doctor,
a forgiving priest...

427
00:33:34,300 --> 00:33:37,500
and a clever accountant. ''

428
00:33:40,900 --> 00:33:45,000
The first two... [Chuckles]
I've never had much use for.

429
00:33:45,100 --> 00:33:48,500
But the third--

430
00:33:53,800 --> 00:33:57,300
Just pretend,
for Christ's sake.

431
00:34:01,000 --> 00:34:04,200
Is that all?

432
00:34:09,000 --> 00:34:12,200
I'm trying to thank you.

433
00:34:12,300 --> 00:34:16,500
I'm saying I couldn't
have done this without you.

434
00:34:19,000 --> 00:34:21,900
The usual thing would be
to acknowledge my gratitude.

435
00:34:22,000 --> 00:34:26,900
It would also, by the way,
be the courteous thing.

436
00:34:26,900 --> 00:34:29,800
You're welcome.

437
00:34:31,900 --> 00:34:33,800
[Sighs]

438
00:34:38,700 --> 00:34:40,900
Get out of here.

439
00:34:44,600 --> 00:34:45,700
[Door Buzzer]

440
00:34:54,300 --> 00:34:57,500
[Schindler]
Klonowska, who is it?

441
00:35:06,800 --> 00:35:09,500
She's so embarrassed.
Look at her.

442
00:35:21,500 --> 00:35:23,800
You know something?
You would like her.

443
00:35:23,900 --> 00:35:25,800
Oskar, please.
What?

444
00:35:25,900 --> 00:35:28,300
I don't have to like her...
just because you do.
You would, though.

445
00:35:28,400 --> 00:35:31,200
It doesn't work that way.

446
00:35:33,600 --> 00:35:36,000
[Door Closing]

447
00:35:43,900 --> 00:35:46,800
You've done well here.

448
00:35:49,200 --> 00:35:51,800
You look wonderful.

449
00:35:54,700 --> 00:35:58,200
- Be careful of the step, miss.
- Mrs. Schindler, Marek.

450
00:36:05,000 --> 00:36:10,800
## [''Gloomy Sunday'']

451
00:36:10,900 --> 00:36:14,900
It's not a charade, all this?
How could it be a charade?

452
00:36:14,900 --> 00:36:17,400
The clothes, the car, the apartment.
Wait a minute.

