Hand und ein deutliches Jawhol!

927
01:14:29,000 --> 01:14:32,600
[Shouts Name]
[Man]
Jawohl.

928
01:14:32,700 --> 01:14:36,300
[Shouts Name]
[Man]
Jawohl.

929
01:14:36,300 --> 01:14:39,600
Keller, Fanni!
Jawohl.

930
01:14:39,700 --> 01:14:44,100
Adalbert, Hermann!
[Man]
Jawohl.

931
01:14:44,200 --> 01:14:46,600
Faber, Dorothea!
[Woman]
Jawohl.

932
01:14:46,700 --> 01:14:50,100
Goldstein, Pola!
[Woman]
Jawohl.

933
01:14:50,200 --> 01:14:53,100
Warmberger, Markus!

934
01:14:53,200 --> 01:14:55,100
Jawohl.

935
01:14:55,200 --> 01:14:57,800
Edelstein, Max!

936
01:14:57,900 --> 01:15:01,800
[Soldiers Continue
Shouting Names]

937
01:15:11,200 --> 01:15:15,600
[Soldiers Continue
Shouting Names]

938
01:15:15,700 --> 01:15:18,300
Appell
abtreten!

939
01:15:18,400 --> 01:15:20,400
Do pracy!
Do pracy!

940
01:15:20,500 --> 01:15:24,300
The worst is over.
We are workers now.

941
01:15:24,400 --> 01:15:28,100
[Man Speaking German
Over Loudspeaker]

942
01:15:40,800 --> 01:15:44,300
[Officer Shouting
In German]

943
01:15:55,100 --> 01:15:58,300
[Officer]
Keine Muedigkeit vorschuetzen!

944
01:16:00,300 --> 01:16:02,700
[Woman Shrieks,
People Shouting]

945
01:16:02,800 --> 01:16:06,200
Oh, God, Amon.

946
01:16:07,400 --> 01:16:10,000
[Officer Shouting
In German]

947
01:16:10,100 --> 01:16:15,100
[Loudspeaker]
Sofort in der Baracke
zurueckmelden!

948
01:16:30,100 --> 01:16:32,000
[Gunshot]

949
01:16:33,200 --> 01:16:36,000
[Man Shouting
In German]

950
01:16:36,100 --> 01:16:39,100
[Reloading Rifle]

951
01:16:39,200 --> 01:16:42,500
[Woman Shrieking]

952
01:16:42,500 --> 01:16:45,500
[Officer Shouting
In German]

953
01:16:53,300 --> 01:16:56,600
[Bones Crack]

954
01:16:56,700 --> 01:17:00,100
[Officer Shouting]
Komm du mal schoen her!
Komm du schoen!

955
01:17:00,200 --> 01:17:02,600
Na komm!
Na komm!

956
01:17:05,700 --> 01:17:09,000
Amon, you're such
a damned fuckin' child!

957
01:17:09,000 --> 01:17:11,200
Wakey, wakey.

958
01:17:15,200 --> 01:17:17,900
[Sighs]

959
01:17:21,000 --> 01:17:24,600
[Woman]
Make coffee.
Make it yourself.

960
01:17:28,400 --> 01:17:31,300
[Grunting]

961
01:17:39,000 --> 01:17:40,000
[Man]
...

962
01:17:40,900 --> 01:17:44,400
The SS will manage certain industries itself
inside Plaszow

963
01:17:44,900 --> 01:17:47,400
a metalworks, brush factory,

964
01:17:47,500 --> 01:17:49,900
another for reprocessing
Jewish clothing...

965
01:17:49,900 --> 01:17:53,900
from the ghettos for use by
bombed-out families back home.

966
01:17:53,900 --> 01:17:57,900
But it's private industry like yours 
that stands to benefit most...

967
01:17:57,900 --> 01:18:00,900
by moving inside the wire of
Commandant Amon Goeth's camp--

968
01:18:00,900 --> 01:18:01,500
No, no, no. Sit, sit.
Julian, how are you?

969
01:18:01,600 --> 01:18:03,100
How are you?
Good to see you, my friend.

970
01:18:03,100 --> 01:18:05,900
Oskar Schindler.
Leo John.

971
01:18:06,000 --> 01:18:09,400
[Whispers, Chuckles]

972
01:18:09,400 --> 01:18:12,700
- Franz, good to see you.
- Hello, Oskar.

973
01:18:12,800 --> 01:18:15,900
- Glad you could join us.
- My pleasure. Julius.
- How are you?

974
01:18:15,900 --> 01:18:20,000
- You lost weight.
- Only in the shoulders.
- Please, everybody, sit down.

975
01:18:20,100 --> 01:18:24,000
- How are you doing?
Oskar Schindler.

976
01:18:25,500 --> 01:18:29,400
- We started without you.
- Fine. I missed anything good?

977
01:18:29,400 --> 01:18:32,200
I was explaining to Herr Bosch
and Herr Madritsch...

978
01:18:32,300 --> 01:18:35,200
some of the benefits of moving their
factories into Plaszow.

979
01:18:35,200 --> 01:18:38,200
I meant the food.
[Chuckles]

980
01:18:39,300 --> 01:18:43,400
Since your labor is housed on-site,
it's available to you at all times.

981
01:18:43,500 --> 01:18:45,700
You can work them
all night if you want.

982
01:18:45,800 --> 01:18:51,300
Your factory policies, whatever
they've been in the past,
they'll continue to be.

983
01:18:51,300 --> 01:18:53,500
They'll be respected.

984
01:18:53,600 --> 01:18:58,900
I have to know, where
do you get a suit like that?
What is that? Is that silk?

985
01:18:58,900 --> 01:19:00,900
Of course.

986
01:19:00,900 --> 01:19:04,200
Ja. It's-- It has
a nice sheen about it.

987
01:19:04,300 --> 01:19:06,200
Thank you.
Very nice.

988
01:19:06,300 --> 01:19:10,100
I'd say I'd get you one,
but the man who made it is probably dead.

989
01:19:10,200 --> 01:19:12,700
I don't know.

990
01:19:12,800 --> 01:19:16,600
[Schindler's Voice]
I go to work the other day.

991
01:19:16,600 --> 01:19:18,900
Nobody's there.

992
01:19:18,900 --> 01:19:22,400
Nobody tells me about this.
I have to find out. I have to go in.

993
01:19:22,500 --> 01:19:27,000
Everybody's gone.

994
01:19:27,100 --> 01:19:29,000
No.
[Sighs]

995
01:19:29,100 --> 01:19:31,200
No.

996
01:19:33,900 --> 01:19:36,500
They're not gone.
They're here.

997
01:19:36,600 --> 01:19:42,600
They're mine!
Every day that goes by, I'm losing money.

998
01:19:42,600 --> 01:19:45,800
Every worker that is shot costs me money.
I have to find somebody else. I have to train them.

999
01:19:45,900 --> 01:19:48,900
We are going to be making so much money
that none of this is going to matter.

1000
01:19:48,900 --> 01:19:50,100
It's bad business.

1001
01:19:53,300 --> 01:19:55,200
[Sniffs]

1002
01:20:03,100 --> 01:20:05,100
Thank you.

1003
01:20:05,100 --> 01:20:07,700
Leave the bottle.

1004
01:20:08,900 --> 01:20:11,100
Take that.

1005
01:20:11,200 --> 01:20:14,800
Lena... thank you.

1006
01:20:24,100 --> 01:20:27,200
Scherner told me
something else about you.

1007
01:20:29,500 --> 01:20:31,900
Yeah?
What's that?

1008
01:20:31,900 --> 01:20:36,600
That you know the meaning
of the word ''gratitude.''

1009
01:20:36,700 --> 01:20:40,200
That it's not
some vague thing with you...

1010
01:20:40,300 --> 01:20:43,500
like it is with others.

1011
01:20:43,500 --> 01:20:47,000
You want to stay
where you are.

1012
01:20:47,100 --> 01:20:50,200
You've got things
going on the side.

1013
01:20:50,300 --> 01:20:52,400
Things are good.

1014
01:20:52,500 --> 01:20:57,000
You don't want anybody
telling you what to do.

1015
01:20:57,100 --> 01:21:01,600
I can understand all that,
you know. I-- I know you.

1016
01:21:03,700 --> 01:21:08,900
What you want...
is your own sub-camp.

1017
01:21:14,300 --> 01:21:17,800
Do you have any idea what is involved?
The paperwork alone?

1018
01:21:17,900 --> 01:21:22,000
You've got to build the thing.
Getting those fucking permits
is enough to drive you crazy.

1019
01:21:22,000 --> 01:21:26,200
Then the engineers show up,
they stand around, they argue
about drainage, foundations,

1020
01:21:26,200 --> 01:21:31,500
codes, exact specifications,
fences four kilometers long,
1,200 kilograms of barbed wire,

1021
01:21:31,600 --> 01:21:34,900
[Chuckling]
6,000 kilograms of electrified
fences, ceramic insulators,

1022
01:21:34,900 --> 01:21:36,700
three cubic meters
of air space per prisoner.

1023
01:21:36,700 --> 01:21:40,800
I'm telling you, you want to shoot somebody.
I've been through it. I know.

1024
01:21:40,800 --> 01:21:44,600
Well, you know.
You've been through it.
[Spits]

1025
01:21:46,500 --> 01:21:49,600
You could make things
easier for me.

1026
01:21:52,600 --> 01:21:54,700
I'd be grateful.

1027
01:21:57,300 --> 01:21:59,700
Aus dem Weg da!

1028
01:22:07,400 --> 01:22:09,700
[Dogs Barking]

1029
01:22:09,800 --> 01:22:13,700
Weitergehen!
Weitergehen!
[Speaking Polish]

1030
01:22:13,800 --> 01:22:14,900
[Whistle Blows]

1031
01:22:15,000 --> 01:22:18,400
Wlewo zwrot!
Trzymac szereg!

1032
01:22:18,500 --> 01:22:21,400
Weitergehen.
Nach links.

1033
01:22:21,500 --> 01:22:24,400
[Dogs Continue Barking]

1034
01:22:26,100 --> 01:22:28,900
[Whistle Blows]

1035
01:22:29,000 --> 01:22:31,000
Where's Stern?

1036
01:22:34,700 --> 01:22:38,800
Goldberg and Chilowicz...
make sure I see my cut...

1037
01:22:38,900 --> 01:22:42,400
from the, uh,
factory owners in this camp,

1038
01:22:42,500 --> 01:22:45,900
leaving you to take care
of my main account--

1039
01:22:46,000 --> 01:22:49,300
the Schindler account.

1040
01:22:49,400 --> 01:22:53,400
He wants his independence.
I gave it to him.

1041
01:22:53,500 --> 01:22:56,400
But independence
costs money.

1042
01:22:56,500 --> 01:22:58,900
This you
understand?

1043
01:23:03,800 --> 01:23:05,700
Look at me.

1044
01:23:16,400 --> 01:23:20,500
Don't forget who
you are working for now.

1045
01:23:25,000 --> 01:23:27,900
[Chattering, Shouting]

1046
01:23:28,000 --> 01:23:30,000
####[Accordion]

1047
01:23:30,100 --> 01:23:33,300
Jawohl!
[Schindler]
Make sure he kisses
each and every one!

1048
01:23:33,400 --> 01:23:36,800
Ja. Now, girls,
everyone.

1049
01:23:39,700 --> 01:23:42,300
We need more wine.
More wine!

1050
01:23:42,400 --> 01:23:46,200
Stand in my place.
Don't let him leave.

1051
01:23:46,200 --> 01:23:48,800
[Laughing, Singing]

1052
01:23:50,900 --> 01:23:54,000
[Chattering,
Shouting Continue]

1053
01:24:02,200 --> 01:24:05,600
## Was passiert denn
in einem Leben ##
Prost! Prost!

1054
01:24:07,600 --> 01:24:10,300
Thank you,
Herr Direktor.

1055
01:24:10,400 --> 01:24:12,800
Prost,
Herr Direktor!

1056
01:24:16,900 --> 01:24:20,400
What are you
doing?
What?
Scratching my head.

1057
01:24:20,500 --> 01:24:24,900
Makes them think we have lice.
Helps them keep their distance.
[Exhales]

1058
01:24:25,000 --> 01:24:27,500
Do you have lice?
Do you have your notebook?

1059
01:24:27,600 --> 01:24:31,200
The calendar on my desk has
the birthdays of our SS friends'
wives and children.

1060
01:24:31,300 --> 01:24:33,900
Don't forget
to send something.

1061
01:24:33,900 --> 01:24:37,400
Record payoffs
to the Main Administration
and Economics Office, the Arm--

1062
01:24:37,500 --> 01:24:41,400
Slower, Stern, slower.
The Armaments Board,
Governor General's Division...

1063
01:24:41,500 --> 01:24:44,400
of the Interior
and Chief of Police as ''fees,''

1064
01:24:44,500 --> 01:24:46,500
and make them
on the first of each month,

1065
01:24:46,600 --> 01:24:48,900
as opposed to individual payoffs
to our SS contacts.

1066
01:24:49,000 --> 01:24:54,400
The list is in the lower drawer
of my desk, which you--
''First of month--''

1067
01:24:54,500 --> 01:24:57,400
SS contacts: list,
lower drawer of my desk,
which you handle...

1068
01:24:57,500 --> 01:25:01,700
as cash contributions
to legitimate charities
sent to each official's office.

1069
01:25:01,800 --> 01:25:04,900
Dealings with
our black market contacts,
listed as suppliers...

1070
01:25:04,900 --> 01:25:08,600
in the legitimate ledger,
are more complicated.
Forget it.

1071
01:25:08,700 --> 01:25:12,600
What do you mean, forget it?
You can't forget it!
It gives me a headache!

1072
01:25:12,700 --> 01:25:16,300
[Dogs Barking]

1073
01:25:16,400 --> 01:25:19,300
[Sighs]

1074
01:25:19,400 --> 01:25:22,800
I couldn't get you
out of here.
I'll be all right.

1075
01:25:22,800 --> 01:25:27,000
Anyway, I'm here
almost every week.
Wednesdays, usually.

1076
01:25:27,000 --> 01:25:30,500
I'll look in on you,
see how you're doing.

1077
01:25:32,600 --> 01:25:36,300
Here, put these
in your pocket.

1078
01:25:36,300 --> 01:25:38,400
Come on.

1079
01:25:41,200 --> 01:25:44,600
[Inhales]
Herr Direktor,
don't let things fall apart.

1080
01:25:44,700 --> 01:25:46,900
I've worked too hard.

1081
01:25:55,200 --> 01:25:59,800
Thanks for--
Good luck.

1082
01:25:59,900 --> 01:26:03,800
## [Music, Shouting
Continue]

1083
01:26:21,600 --> 01:26:24,000
Achtung, Muetzen ab!

1084
01:26:33,900 --> 01:26:36,400
- Work!
- An die Arbeit!

1085
01:26:50,100 --> 01:26:51,600
What are you making?

1086
01:26:51,900 --> 01:26:54,400
Hinges, sir.

1087
01:26:57,300 --> 01:27:00,900
Ja, I've got some workers
coming in tomorrow.
Where are they from again?

1088
01:27:01,000 --> 01:27:03,400
Yugoslavia,
Herr Kommandant.

1089
01:27:03,400 --> 01:27:05,700
I've got to make room.

1090
01:27:08,100 --> 01:27:11,400
Make me a hinge.
Yes, sir.

1091
01:27:16,700 --> 01:27:19,700
[Guards Muttering]

1092
01:27:42,800 --> 01:27:46,000
Keep going,
you're doing well.

1093
01:27:46,100 --> 01:27:48,200
Says he's
doing well.

1094
01:27:54,900 --> 01:27:57,600
Oh, that's very good.

1095
01:27:57,600 --> 01:28:01,600
But I'm a bit confused,
and perhaps you can help me.

1096
01:28:01,700 --> 01:28:05,100
What I don't understand
is that you've been working...

1097
01:28:05,200 --> 01:28:08,900
since I think, what,
about six this morning?

1098
01:28:10,500 --> 01:28:14,900
Yet such a small pile
of hinges.

1099
01:28:22,400 --> 01:28:25,300
[Train Whistle Blows]

1100
01:28:33,700 --> 01:28:35,700
[Gun Clicks]

1101
01:28:44,000 --> 01:28:46,900
[Gun Clicks]
Oh, Christ.
May I try that, sir?

1102
01:28:46,900 --> 01:28:49,200
Check the angle-lever.
Maybe it's bent.

1103
01:28:49,200 --> 01:28:52,700
No, no.
You wouldn't hear a click
if it was the angle-lever.

1104
01:28:52,800 --> 01:28:55,200
Maybe it's the pin.
Maybe the pin shaft is greasy.
Ja, come on.

1105
01:28:55,200 --> 01:28:58,300
What did I just say?
Here.

1106
01:28:59,700 --> 01:29:03,300
[Gun Clicks]
Herr Kommandant,

1107
01:29:03,400 --> 01:29:07,900
I beg to report
that my heap ofhinges
was so unsatisfactory...

1108
01:29:08,000 --> 01:29:12,300
because the machines
were being recalibrated
this morning.

1109
01:29:12,400 --> 01:29:17,300
[Gun Clicks]
I w-was put on
to shoveling coal.

1110
01:29:17,400 --> 01:29:21,700
[Gun Clicking]

1111
01:29:26,400 --> 01:29:29,200
[Grunts, Yells]

1112
01:29:29,300 --> 01:29:31,900
[Gasps, Sobbing]

1113
01:29:41,100 --> 01:29:43,200
Strange, huh?

1114
01:29:43,300 --> 01:29:45,200
Yeah.

1115
01:29:50,000 --> 01:29:53,200
Thank you, Muek.

1116
01:29:53,300 --> 01:29:57,200
Ah, Lisiek.
Don't touch the leather,
it's just been oiled.

1117
01:29:57,300 --> 01:29:59,000
Rottenfuehrer.
Oh, for me?

1118
01:29:59,000 --> 01:30:02,700
Oh, thank you very much,
Herr Direktor. Thank you.
[Stern] Herr Direktor!

1119
01:30:02,800 --> 01:30:05,300
Herr Direktor!

1120
01:30:07,900 --> 01:30:10,500
Herr Direktor!

1121
01:30:11,700 --> 01:30:13,700
He was making
hinges slowly.

1122
01:30:13,800 --> 01:30:18,700
So the man can turn out a hinge
in less than a minute.
Why the long story? Hmm?

1123
01:30:45,800 --> 01:30:47,700
[Machines Rumbling]

1124
01:30:47,800 --> 01:30:50,600
Thank you, sir.
You're welcome.

1125
01:30:53,800 --> 01:30:57,800
Nobody knows
who stole the chicken, hmm?
Tell him about the chicken.

1126
01:30:57,800 --> 01:31:02,600
A man walks around
with a chicken and
nobody notices this.

1127
01:31:02,700 --> 01:31:05,200
Save yourselves.

1128
01:31:05,300 --> 01:31:07,700
Tell him
about the chicken.

1129
01:31:23,400 --> 01:31:25,500
Still nobody knows.

1130
01:31:30,400 --> 01:31:33,800
[Sobbing]

1131
01:31:37,200 --> 01:31:41,000
It was you.
You committed this crime.

1132
01:31:41,000 --> 01:31:43,400
No, sir.
But you know who, though.

1133
01:31:43,500 --> 01:31:45,800
Yes.
Who?

1134
01:31:45,900 --> 01:31:48,900
[Sobbing]
Him!

1135
01:31:52,400 --> 01:31:56,300
He's very gifted.
Yeah, sure.
Bring him over.

1136
01:31:59,100 --> 01:32:03,000
Yes, sir.
Thank you.

1137
01:32:09,100 --> 01:32:12,000
Thank you again,
Herr Direktor.
You're welcome again.

1138
01:32:12,000 --> 01:32:15,800
It's an honor to work
for such a great company.
It's great to have you.

1139
01:32:15,900 --> 01:32:20,100
I promise to learn everything
about enamelware production.
That's great.

1140
01:32:32,600 --> 01:32:36,800
Hello?
Miss Elsa Krause is here.
I only need five minutes.

1141
01:32:36,800 --> 01:32:39,600
She wants to speak
to the Herr Direktor.

1142
01:32:39,600 --> 01:32:42,900
[Typewriter Keys Clicking]

1143
01:32:59,100 --> 01:33:01,300
Yes.

1144
01:33:05,500 --> 01:33:07,800
He won't see you.

1145
01:33:38,400 --> 01:33:40,500
Please, sit down.

1146
01:33:43,700 --> 01:33:46,600
Pernod?
Cognac?
Uh, no.
No, thank you.

1147
01:33:47,800 --> 01:33:50,700
So, what
can I do for you?

1148
01:33:54,700 --> 01:33:57,800
[Nervous Chuckle]
They say that no one
dies here.

1149
01:33:57,800 --> 01:34:00,500
They say your factory
is a haven.

1150
01:34:03,300 --> 01:34:05,600
They say you are good.

1151
01:34:08,600 --> 01:34:10,800
Who says that?

1152
01:34:10,900 --> 01:34:13,000
Everyone.

1153
01:34:19,400 --> 01:34:22,300
My name is Regina Perlman,
not Elsa Krause.

1154
01:34:22,400 --> 01:34:25,600
I've been living in Krakow
on false papers since
the ghetto massacre.

1155
01:34:25,700 --> 01:34:27,200
My parents are in Plaszow.

1156
01:34:27,300 --> 01:34:31,800
Their names are
Chana and Jakob Perlman.

1157
01:34:31,900 --> 01:34:35,700
They are older people.
They are killing older people
now in Plaszow.

1158
01:34:35,700 --> 01:34:39,700
They bury them
up in the forest. Look...

1159
01:34:39,800 --> 01:34:42,700
[Sighs]
I don't have any money.

1160
01:34:42,800 --> 01:34:45,700
I, I borrowed
these clothes.

1161
01:34:48,400 --> 01:34:50,500
I'm begging you.

1162
01:34:50,600 --> 01:34:54,500
Please, please
bring them here.

1163
01:34:54,600 --> 01:34:57,100
I don't do that.

1164
01:34:57,100 --> 01:35:01,100
You've been misled.
I ask one thing:

1165
01:35:01,100 --> 01:35:04,400
whether or not a worker
has certain skills.

1166
01:35:04,400 --> 01:35:07,300
My father is an importer,
not a metalworker.

1167
01:35:07,400 --> 01:35:11,300
[Continues Arguing]
Such activities are illegal.
You will not entrap me!

1168
01:35:11,400 --> 01:35:15,700
Cry, and I will
have you arrested.
I swear to God!

1169
01:35:15,800 --> 01:35:18,300
[Mutters, Sobbing]

1170
01:35:26,400 --> 01:35:29,100
People die.
It's a fact of life.

1171
01:35:29,200 --> 01:35:33,000
He wants to kill everybody?
Great! What am I supposed
to do about it?

1172
01:35:33,100 --> 01:35:35,800
Bring everybody over?
Is that what you think?

1173
01:35:35,900 --> 01:35:38,800
Send them over to Schindler.
Send them all!

1174
01:35:38,800 --> 01:35:42,500
His place is a haven,
didn't you know?
It's not a factory.

1175
01:35:42,600 --> 01:35:44,900
It's not an enterprise
of any kind.

1176
01:35:44,900 --> 01:35:47,800
It's a haven for rabbis
and orphans...

1177
01:35:47,900 --> 01:35:51,200
and people with
no skills whatsoever!

1178
01:35:52,400 --> 01:35:56,000
[Sighs]
You think I don't know
what you're doing?

1179
01:35:56,700 --> 01:35:59,700
You're so quiet all the time.
I know, I know!

1180
01:36:00,400 --> 01:36:02,800
Are you losing money?
That's not the point!

1181
01:36:03,400 --> 01:36:06,600
What other point is ... 
It's dangerous! It's dangerous to me!

1182
01:36:11,300 --> 01:36:14,300
You have to understand.
Goeth is under enormous pressure.

1183
01:36:15,000 --> 01:36:17,700
You have to think of it
in his situation.

1184
01:36:18,400 --> 01:36:20,800
He's got this
whole place to run.

1185
01:36:21,400 --> 01:36:23,800
He's responsible for everything here,
all these people.

1186
01:36:24,000 --> 01:36:26,900
He's got a lot of things
to worry about.

1187
01:36:27,400 --> 01:36:30,900
And he's got the war
which brings out the worst in people.

1188
01:36:31,700 --> 01:36:34,500
Never the good, always the bad.
Always the bad.

1189
01:36:37,300 --> 01:36:41,200
But in normal circumstances
he wouldn't be like this.
He'd be all right.

1190
01:36:42,000 --> 01:36:45,000
There'd just be the good
aspects of him which--

1191
01:36:45,600 --> 01:36:48,700
[Chuckles]
He's a wonderful crook.

1192
01:36:49,300 --> 01:36:53,000
A man who loves good food,
good wine, the ladies, making money

1193
01:36:53,800 --> 01:36:55,700
Killing.

1194
01:36:56,100 --> 01:36:58,400
He can't enjoy it.

1195
01:36:59,000 --> 01:37:01,600
Bejski told me the other day,
somebody escaped...

1196
01:37:02,200 --> 01:37:04,500
from a work detail
outside the wire.

1197
01:37:05,000 --> 01:37:08,400
[Gunshots]
Goeth lined up everybody
from the missing man's barracks.

1198
01:37:09,200 --> 01:37:12,600
He shot the man to the left of Bejski,
the man to the right of him.

1199
01:37:13,300 --> 01:37:16,400
He walked down the line
shooting every other man with the pistol.

1200
01:37:22,100 --> 01:37:24,200
Twenty-five.

1201
01:37:28,500 --> 01:37:31,600
What do you want me to do about it?
Nothing, nothing.

1202
01:37:32,300 --> 01:37:34,200
We're just talking.

1203
01:37:46,300 --> 01:37:47,900
''Perlman.''